# Component Rules

## RSC vs Client boundary

Use React Server Components for data fetching. Add `'use client'` only for interactivity (event handlers, state, effects).

```tsx
// ✅ GOOD — RSC fetches, passes data down
// app/page.tsx (server)
export default async function Page() {
  const result = await getStats();
  if (!result.ok) return <DataError message={result.error.message} />;
  return <SummaryPanel stats={result.data} />;
}

// ✅ GOOD — client component in components/
'use client';
export const FilterChips = ({ onChange }: FilterChipsProps) => { ... };

// ❌ BAD — 'use client' on a data-loading page
'use client';
export default async function Page() { ... }
```

## Component style — arrow functions + named exports

**Default for all components** (RSC and `'use client'` alike): `export const ComponentName = (...) => { ... }`. No `export default`, no `function ComponentName()`.

Applies to every file under `components/`. `'use client'` does not change this rule — it only marks the client boundary.

Helper functions outside the component (e.g. `formatDate`, `toSize`, `subscribe`) may stay as `function` declarations.

```tsx
// ✅ GOOD — RSC
export const SummaryPanel = ({ stats }: SummaryPanelProps) => { ... };

// ✅ GOOD — client
'use client';
export const ThemeToggle = () => { ... };

// ❌ BAD
export default function SummaryPanel() { ... }
```

Import with named imports:

```tsx
import { Skeleton } from '@/components/Skeleton/Skeleton';
import { StatCard } from './components/StatCard/StatCard';
```

**Exception — Next.js route files only:** `app/page.tsx`, `layout.tsx`, `loading.tsx`, `error.tsx`, `not-found.tsx`, etc. must `export default` the route entry (framework requirement). Define the route component as an arrow `const`, then `export default RouteName` at the bottom if you prefer consistency inside the file.

```tsx
// ✅ GOOD — app/error.tsx
'use client';
const ErrorPage = ({ error, reset }: ErrorPageProps) => <DataError ... />;
export default ErrorPage;
```

## Props interface naming

Name the props interface `ComponentNameProps` — never bare `Props`.

```tsx
// ✅ GOOD
interface SummaryPanelProps {
  stats: Stats;
}
export const SummaryPanel = ({ stats }: SummaryPanelProps) => { ... };

// ❌ BAD
interface Props { stats: Stats; }
```

Same rule for route components in `app/` (`ErrorPageProps`, `HomePageProps`, etc.).

## File layout — no barrel `index.ts`

Each component lives in `components/<Name>/<Name>.tsx`. Import the file directly — no `index.ts` re-exports in `components/`.

## Styling — CSS Modules + theme variables

```tsx
// ✅ GOOD
import styles from './SummaryPanel.module.css';
<div className={styles.panel}>...</div>
```

Theme colors via CSS variables defined in `app/globals.css`:
`--color-bg`, `--color-text`, `--color-accent`. Never hardcode hex in components.

## Accessibility

- Use semantic HTML: `<table>`, `<thead>`, `<th scope="col">`, `<button>`, `<nav>`.
- Sortable columns: `<th aria-sort="ascending">`.
- Keyboard navigation on table rows: `tabIndex={0}` + `onKeyDown` for Enter/Space.
- Contrast: WCAG AA (≥4.5:1 normal text, ≥3:1 large) in both light and dark themes.

## Responsive layout

Desktop: `<table>` layout. Mobile (`max-width: 640px`): card layout via CSS only — no JS breakpoint detection.

```css
/* components/RequirementsTable.module.css */
@media (max-width: 640px) {
  thead { display: none; }
  tr { display: block; margin-bottom: 1rem; }
}
```
